115
00:11:01,995 --> 00:11:04,498
Quote, “Sentimental favourite
Chris Marshall...

116
00:11:04,665 --> 00:11:05,707
...blah, blah, blah...

117
00:11:05,874 --> 00:11:08,627
...son of late Senator
Graham Marshall, blah, blah...

118
00:11:08,794 --> 00:11:11,964
...is expected to run for his father's
seat in the next election.”

119
00:11:12,130 --> 00:11:14,633
-End quote.
-Let me see that. Let me see it, Jerry.

120
00:11:14,842 --> 00:11:16,760
You don't need to see it. No.

121
00:11:16,927 --> 00:11:19,972
-Give it here.
-Fine. But I hadn't finished it yet.

122
00:11:20,347 --> 00:11:23,058
”Sentimental favourite
and playboy politico...

123
00:11:23,225 --> 00:11:26,562
...Assemblyman Chris Marshall....”
Guess you missed a few words, Jer.

124
00:11:26,728 --> 00:11:28,313
What, “playboy”?
That's a compliment.

125
00:11:28,522 --> 00:11:32,359
”Who called off his engagement
to über babe Daniella Van Graas...

126
00:11:32,526 --> 00:11:35,737
...arrives in town solo.”
Respectful, huh?

127
00:11:36,446 --> 00:11:40,075
Well, listen, you know, you're
a public figure. It’s news. So what?

128
00:11:40,242 --> 00:11:42,536
We were never engaged.
Whose side are you on?

129
00:11:42,703 --> 00:11:45,289
Yours. That's why sometimes
you have to listen to me.

130
00:11:45,455 --> 00:11:47,749
-Every now and again it might be nice.
-Here.

131
00:11:47,916 --> 00:11:49,710
Welcome to the Beresford,
Mr. Marshall.

132
00:11:49,877 --> 00:11:50,961
-Hello.
-My name is Lionel.

133
00:11:51,128 --> 00:11:52,462
-Lionel?
-I’m the floor butler.

134
00:11:52,629 --> 00:11:54,882
lf there's anything you need,
please call me.

135
00:11:55,048 --> 00:11:58,886
Thank you. This is Jerry,
and this is Dan, and the dog is Rufus.

136
00:11:59,052 --> 00:12:01,096
Thank you, Lionel.
Nice to meet you. Thanks.

137
00:12:01,263 --> 00:12:04,725
We'll call you if we need you. Chris,
will you look at me, please? Chris?

138
00:12:04,892 --> 00:12:07,561
-Can you look at me for a minute?
-What? I am looking at you.

139
00:12:07,728 --> 00:12:10,063
We're going to Maddox's thing
on Monday night.

140
00:12:10,272 --> 00:12:11,273
No, Jerry, we're not.

141
00:12:11,440 --> 00:12:14,526
See, this is when I wish your
old man were here to back me up.

142
00:12:14,735 --> 00:12:16,320
-What?
-I said, I wish your old man...

143
00:12:16,486 --> 00:12:19,406
-...were here to back me up.
-My father had no use for that man.

144
00:12:19,573 --> 00:12:22,743
Your father knew how
to use that man.

145
00:12:23,285 --> 00:12:24,953
-Where are you going?
-What?

146
00:12:25,120 --> 00:12:28,207
-That depends. Where are you going?
-Bathroom. Alone.

147
00:12:28,373 --> 00:12:30,417
-Yeah. Fine. Go. Great. Yeah. Sure.
-Thank you.

148
00:12:30,584 --> 00:12:32,711
Call me if you need anything.

149
00:12:37,508 --> 00:12:39,927
Oh, my God. I’m sorry, sir.

150
00:12:44,264 --> 00:12:46,016
Thank you.

151
00:12:59,863 --> 00:13:01,532
Sir.

152
00:13:02,658 --> 00:13:05,494
Thank you. Thank you very much.
I’m so clumsy.

153
00:13:05,661 --> 00:13:08,163
-Happens to all of us. Here.
-Thank you.

154
00:13:08,330 --> 00:13:10,332
-Let me help you.
-Thank you.

155
00:13:11,458 --> 00:13:14,503
-Where do those go?
-Caroline Lane. Park Suite.

156
00:13:14,670 --> 00:13:18,090
She just checked in with a request
for immediate unpack and press.

157
00:13:18,257 --> 00:13:21,260
Here. Blood and Dolce:

158
00:13:22,678 --> 00:13:26,640
Thank you. Thank you.

159
00:13:27,808 --> 00:13:30,269
I mean, there are limits.

160
00:13:31,645 --> 00:13:36,066
You're so bad. You really are, Rach.

161
00:13:36,233 --> 00:13:38,902
Yes, just hold on a second.

162
00:13:39,069 --> 00:13:41,864
Thank you. Anything, I mean,
it's up and down.

163
00:13:42,030 --> 00:13:45,117
One day, we're looking at rings,
and the next day, we're breaking up.

164
00:13:45,284 --> 00:13:47,995
Yeah. No way.

165
00:13:48,162 --> 00:13:49,997
So l...

166
00:13:50,164 --> 00:13:55,836
...had my assistant accidentally forward
my calendar for the week to his e-mail.

167
00:13:56,336 --> 00:14:01,508
Of course, I added a few extra lunch
dates and dinner parties with my ex.

168
00:14:01,675 --> 00:14:04,011
Fantastic, right?

169
00:14:04,553 --> 00:14:07,973
